&lt;p&gt;   **&lt;span class=&quot;error&quot;&gt;&amp;#91;Benjamin Bentmann&amp;#93;&lt;/span&gt;(&lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=bentmann)**&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=bentmann)**&lt;/a&gt; opened **&lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/MCHECKSTYLE-85&quot; title=&quot;Make tests platform-independent&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;MCHECKSTYLE-85&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;MCHECKSTYLE-85&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt;(&lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/MCHECKSTYLE-85?redirect=false)**&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/MCHECKSTYLE-85?redirect=false)**&lt;/a&gt; and commented&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;   The test suite of the plugin uses the the JVM&apos;s default locale to get its resource bundle. However, `AbstractMavenReport.execute()` will always use the English locale when calling `MavenReport.generate()`. Hence, the tests will search for say German strings in a report generated from English resources...&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;   By the way, the current head of the maven-reporting-impl simply throws a `MojoExecutionException` from `AbstractMavenReport.execute()`. All tests will fail once the plugin updates its dependencies. Not to mention that the report cannot be generated from the command line any more, pitty.&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;p&gt;   &amp;#8212;&lt;/p&gt;

